SIMPLE: jubilate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Jubilate
<hw>Ju`bi*la"te</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., imperat. of
<ets>jubilare</ets> to shout for joy.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The third Sunday after Easter; -- so called because
the introit is the 66th Psalm, which, in the Latin version, begins with
the words, ⟦ldquo⟧Jubilate Deo.⟦rdquo⟧</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A name of the 100th Psalm; -- so called from its
opening word in the Latin version.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jubilate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Jubilate
<hw>Ju"bi*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>jubilatus</ets>, <ets>p. p.</ets> of <ets>jubilare</ets>.]</ety>
<def>To exult; to rejoice.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>De
Quincey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jubilation</ent>⟦br⟧
